    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nIn various places a number of us get this warning:\n\n```\nnumpy.ndarray size changed, may indicate binary incompatibility. Expected 16 from C header, got 96 from PyObject\n```\nIn particular, with the netCDF4 lib:\n\nhttps://github.com/Unidata/netcdf4-python/issues/1354\n\nand who knows what else -- it's always a bit hard to tell where it's coming from, and seems to only happen with some combinations of packages ...\n\nWith a bunch of digging, it seems that warning is coming from Cython-generated code (maybe??)\n\nAnd even numpy thinks it's unnecessary:\n\n```\n    # Filter out Cython harmless warnings\n    warnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\", message=\"numpy.dtype size changed\")\n    warnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\", message=\"numpy.ufunc size changed\")\n    warnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\", message=\"numpy.ndarray size changed\")\n```\n\nIf the numpy project thinks they are harmless, why is Cython generating them ???\n\n\n\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\nIt only seems to show up with some combination of packages -- netCDF4 and xarray for instance, be depending on what order things are imported.\n\nI have been unable to reproduce using a simple example ...\n\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nno useless warning raised :-)\n\n\n\n### OS\n\nat least Linux and Mac -- I think Windows, too.\n\n### Python version\n\n3.8 -- 3.14 !\n\n### Cython version\n\nIt's been there for a good while ... all of 3.* maybe before that?\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
