            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "It's a generic mechanism. Here's some (very artificial) non-Numpy code that triggers it:\n\n```\ncdef extern from *:\n    \"\"\"\n    struct FakeList {\n        PyObject_HEAD\n        double array[500];\n    };\n    \"\"\"\n    cdef class __builtin__.list[object FakeList]:\n        pass\n```\n\nIf I compile and try to import that module I get\n\n```\nValueError: builtins.list size changed, may indicate binary incompatibility. Expected 4016 from C header, got 40 from PyObject\n```\n\n> Or would that be that an extension may have been built with a different version of numpy than its is finding at run time?\n\nYes that's the main thing that the mechanism is designed to check for.\n\n> But if that's the case, why are they getting triggered when there isn't an actual problem\n\nBecause for almost any other code it is an actual problem.\n\n> so any code that's using numpy will have these suppressed anyway, unless some other part of the system turns them back on [*].\n\nThe Numpy filters specifically look for the Numpy type-names so they won't be suppressing errors from other modules.\n\n> but it seems there may be a way to tell Cython not to do this check?\n\nIt's the `check_size` option to a which can be one of `error`, `warn`, `ignore`.   In my example it'd be\n\n```\ncdef class __builtin__.list[object FakeList, check_size ignore]:\n```\n\nAlthough looking at Numpy's definition of `ndarray`, they include `check_size ignore` so if you're seeing it you've got an old/odd version of *something* (either Cython or Numpy I think).\n\n-------------------------------------------------\n\nI am trying to relax some of these checks as part of the Stable ABI+freethreading opaque object work too. At very least it's possible to safely use an empty type for example.",
